commentBody:
@Justin 

Oh, I greatly loved that clue also, but alas, it has basically been used before -- [Memorable 70s Ford] and a couple of others -- and I reserve my list for original clues.  




Et tu emu.

@Will

Agreed! It’s a great moment when a puzzle weaves together disparate things. 

I liked this one!

@T Jones 
Yeah, duh on me!  
Maybe I need to keep my glasses on, or else slow down, or both!

@Lewis 

Four. But one is slangy and another is slangier.

(If you don't like the word "slangier" pronounce it so it rhymes with "Tangier". It's fun.)

@Steve D

The crossword has always included references to pop culture.

“Am I so out of touch? No, it’s the children who are wrong.”

@Andy 
Not sure what your point is here.  

Anything, certainly anything mechanical, is not "renewable" in the sense of self-reproducing.

@Eric 

The convention is that if the answer is an abbreviation, initialism or acronym, there clue should signal that. 

The converse is not true; an abbreviation, etc. in the clue doesn’t mean that the answer cannot be a “regular” word.

@Megan

If you're going for a sweet term of endearment for your beau/bae, then it'd be HON (short for "honey"). If you're going for a sly suggestion that they're a scary, coarse and aggressive Attila, then you might spell it HuN, but otherwise, "HON" should be correct.

If you want to get into a REAL argument and imply that they shot first (or didn't), then call them HAN.

@Bob T.,

I noticed too. I wrote out a comment to address someone’s concern and saw that it wouldn’t go through. 

Seemed early to me. 510 comments is a lot, but far from the record.

@Hardroch 
I found the above Sunday puzzle to be so remarkable that I went back to look at some of the commentary that day. David from Weston wrote in to point out a bit of the history of word ladders and I was surprised to learn that they seem to have been invented by Lewis Carroll (Christmas Day, 1877). A quick look at the Wiki entry provides some interesting background as well as theory, such as the relevance of the “Hamming distance” between the first and last word. Anyone working on Lewis’s (no, our own yoga dude from NC) post-puzzle FAVA/NADA  puzzle may want to read up on this. Start with:

